==English==

===Etymology===
{{m|en|noodnik}} is attested since 1925, {{m|en||nudnik}} since 1929. From {{der|en|yi|נודניק|tr=nudnik}} < root of {{m|yi|נודיען||to bore|tr=nudyen}} + {{m|yi|־ניק||noun-forming suffix|tr=-nik}}. Ultimately from {{der|en|sla-pro|*nuda}} < {{der|en|ine-pro|*neuti-||need}} < {{m|ine-pro|*nau-||death, to be exhausted}}.

Compare Russian {{m|ru|нудный||tedious|tr=núdnyj}}, Ukrainian {{m|uk|нудний||tedious|tr=núdnýj}}, Polish {{m|pl|nudny||boring}}, Old Church Slavonic {{m|cu|ноудити||tr=nuditi}} or {{m|cu|нѫдити||to compell|tr=nǫditi}}, Hebrew {{m|he|נוּדְנִיק||[[nag#Verb|nag]]}} and English {{m|en|-nik}}.[[Category:English words suffixed with -nik]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A person who is very [[annoy]]ing; a [[persistent]] [[nag]].
# A [[bore]]; a boring person.
# A [[pest]] of a person; a [[jerk]].

